ws British conflicts with other nations over different regions as well as its eventual challenge to Leopold of Belgium’s rule of the Congo. The reports, speeches, treatises, proclamations, letters, and cartoons assembled here include works by Henry M. Stanley, David Livingstone, Joseph Conrad, G. W. F. Hegel, Winston Churchill, Charles Darwin, and Arthur Conan Doyle. A number of pieces highlight the proliferation of companies chartered to pursue Africa’s gold, diamonds, and oil—particularly Cecil J. Rhodes’s British South Africa Company and Frederick Lugard’s Royal Niger Company. Other documents describe debacles on the continent—such as the defeat of General Gordon in Khartoum and the Anglo-Boer War—and the criticism of imperial maneuvers by proto-human rights activists including George Washington Williams, Mark Twain, Olive Schreiner, and E.D. Morel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aArnold, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBagehot, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaring, Evelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelloc, Hilaire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerriedale Keith, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlunt, Wilfred S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBooth, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchan, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlyle, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Mia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Mia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel